[2]
Date: Mon, 07 Apr 1997 10:27:22 -0500
From: "C. Jon Hinkle hinklc.kc.nw.doh" <HinklC@Mail.Health.State.MO.US>
Subject: PRO/EDR> Hepatitis A, strawberries - USA (03) -Reply
As a Communicable Disease Coordinator working for the Missouri Department of
Health at the District level (I have jurisdiction over 20 counties
accounting for about 20% of the population of the state) in a state that
ranked 5th overall in the number of cases of Hep A last year, I may be able
to shed some light on this. [The apparent selective distribution of
contamination. MHJ]
In any foodborne illness, the distribution of the disease-producing agent
within the food is unlikely to be homogenous. In the case of strawberries
contaminated by (presumably fecal material containing) hepatitis A virus,
which, unlike bacterial agents, does not grow out in food, the distribution
could be limited to only a few containers in a particular lot.
I cannot speak specifically to this incident, since I have had no direct
contact with the investigation, but my experience would be that the entire
lot that supplied the suspect food, as well as other lots that may have come
from the same general processing batch (especially if the records describing
the batches were not too specific) would be candidates for recall.
Given the relatively restricted supply of immune globulin (IG), and the high
potential number of people exposed, I'm sure the decision about which lots
to list, and which kids to shoot was cause for much thought and debate.
DISCLAIMER: The above is my personal opinion, and NOT the stated nor
implied position of the Missouri Department of Health.
---
C. Jon Hinkle
Communicable Disease Coordinator
Northwestern District, MO Dept of Health
